ðŸ“– **Description:**
    The `bzdiff` command works like `diff`, but it is designed to work with files compressed using `bzip2`. It shows the differences between two `bzip2` compressed files without needing to decompress them first.

âš™ï¸ **Options:**
    ðŸ”¹ `bzdiff file1.bz2 file2.bz2` --> ðŸ“ Shows the differences between `file1.bz2` and `file2.bz2`. It also supports the same options as the `diff` command.
    ðŸ”¹ `bzdiff -u file1.bz2 file2.bz2` --> ðŸ”„ Shows differences in "unified diff" format, which is very useful for creating patches.
    ðŸ”¹ `bzdiff -c file1.bz2 file2.bz2` --> ðŸ“„ Shows differences in "context diff" format, which includes a few lines of context before and after the changes.

ðŸ›  **Examples:**

    $ bzdiff file1.bz2 file2.bz2

    ðŸ”¹ Displays the differences between `file1.bz2` and `file2.bz2` in the terminal.

    $ bzdiff -u old_version.bz2 new_version.bz2 > patch.txt

    ðŸ”¹ Creates a `patch.txt` file that contains the differences between `old_version.bz2` and `new_version.bz2` in "unified diff" format. This file can be used to update `old_version.bz2` to `new_version.bz2`.

